{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Hj2ym59YwARSZ4cQaKQWcN","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t\"\"\"Declarative workflow definitions for the PRD harness.\n2\t\n3\tA ``Workflow`` is a named, ordered list of ``Task`` s that implement one\n4\tkind of PRD. Three task types compose a workflow:\n5\t\n6\t- :class:`BuiltIn` — reference a deterministic primitive by name. The\n7\t  set is fixed by the harness package (``builtins.py``): ``ensure_worktree``,\n8\t  ``set_status``, ``commit``, ``push_branch``, ``create_pr``, etc.\n9\t- :class:`AgentTask` — invoke Claude Code with composed prompts, a tool\n10\t  allowlist, and a model selection. This is the only task type where\n11\t  actual code gets written.\n12\t- :class:`ShellTask` — run a deterministic shell command inside the\n13\t  worktree. Used for verification (``just test``, ``pnpm storybook:build``)\n14\t  with an ``on_failure`` policy.\n15\t\n16\tWorkflows live in ``tools/prd-harness/workflows/<name>/workflow.py`` modules\n17\tthat export a top-level ``workflow`` attribute. The loader discovers them\n18\tand the runner dispatches each task in order against an\n19\t:class:`ExecutionContext` that threads mutable state (worktree path, branch\n20\tname, agent output, PR URL, etc.) between tasks.\n21\t\n22\tThis module intentionally contains no I/O, no subprocess calls, and no\n23\tdependency on ``prd.py`` at import time. It's pure data — the shapes that\n24\tworkflow authors and the runner both plug into.\n25\t\"\"\"\n26\t\n27\tfrom __future__ import annotations\n28\t\n29\timport logging\n30\tfrom dataclasses import dataclass, field\n31\tfrom pathlib import Path\n32\tfrom typing import TYPE_CHECKING, Any, Callable, Literal\n33\t\n34\tif TYPE_CHECKING:\n35\t    from filelock import FileLock\n36\t\n37\t    from .prd import PRD\n38\t\n39\t\n40\t# ---------- type aliases ----------\n41\t\n42\t\n43\tOnFailure = Literal[\"fail\", \"retry_agent\", \"ignore\"]\n44\t\"\"\"Policy for a :class:`ShellTask` when the command exits non-zero.\n45\t\n46\t- ``\"fail\"``: abort the workflow with an error (default).\n47\t- ``\"retry_agent\"``: re-invoke the preceding :class:`AgentTask` once with\n48\t  the verify prompts and the failed check output, then retry the shell\n49\t  task once. If it still fails, abort.\n50\t- ``\"ignore\"``: log the failure and continue with the next task. Useful\n51\t  for advisory checks that shouldn't block progress.\n52\t\"\"\"\n53\t\n54\t\n55\tStatus = Literal[\n56\t    \"draft\", \"ready\", \"in-progress\", \"review\", \"done\", \"blocked\", \"cancelled\"\n57\t]\n58\t\"\"\"All PRD lifecycle statuses. Mirrors the enum in ``docs/prd/_schema.yaml``.\"\"\"\n59\t\n60\t\n61\tAppliesToPredicate = Callable[[\"PRD\", dict[str, \"PRD\"]], bool]\n62\t\"\"\"Two-argument predicate deciding whether a workflow applies to a PRD.\n63\t\n64\tTakes the target PRD plus the full PRD set so predicates that need\n65\tsibling or ancestor context (e.g. ``planning`` checking\n66\t``is_fully_decomposed``) can reach for it. Simple predicates like\n67\t``lambda prd, prds: \"ui\" in prd.tags`` ignore the second argument.\n68\t\"\"\"\n69\t\n70\t\n71\t# ---------- Task hierarchy ----------\n72\t\n73\t\n74\tclass Task:\n75\t    \"\"\"Marker base class for all task types.\n76\t\n77\t    Deliberately not a ``@dataclass`` — subclasses define their own fields\n78\t    and don't share any, so dataclass inheritance would add complexity with\n79\t    no benefit. The class exists purely for ``isinstance()`` dispatch in\n80\t    the runner's task loop.\n81\t    \"\"\"\n82\t\n83\t\n84\t@dataclass\n85\tclass BuiltIn(Task):\n86\t    \"\"\"Reference a deterministic primitive from the ``BUILTINS`` registry.\n87\t\n88\t    The runner looks up ``name`` in ``darkfactory.builtins.BUILTINS`` and\n89\t    calls the registered function with ``(ctx, **kwargs)``. String values\n90\t    in ``kwargs`` are formatted via :meth:`ExecutionContext.format_string`\n91\t    before the call, so workflow authors can use ``{prd_id}``-style\n92\t    placeholders.\n93\t\n94\t    Example::\n95\t\n96\t        BuiltIn(\"commit\", kwargs={\"message\": \"chore(prd): {prd_id} start work\"})\n97\t\n98\t    The runner resolves ``{prd_id}`` at execution time; the workflow\n99\t    definition stays free of runtime state.\n100\t    \"\"\"\n101\t\n102\t    name: str\n103\t    kwargs: dict[str, Any] = field(default_factory=dict)\n104\t\n105\t\n106\t@dataclass\n107\tclass AgentTask(Task):\n108\t    \"\"\"Invoke Claude Code with composed prompts and a restricted tool allowlist.\n109\t\n110\t    The runner (see ``runner.py``) performs these steps:\n111\t\n112\t    1. Read each path in :attr:`prompts` relative to the workflow's\n113\t       directory (set by the loader) and concatenate the file contents.\n114\t    2. Substitute ``{{PRD_ID}}``/``{{PRD_TITLE}}``/``{{PRD_PATH}}``/etc.\n115\t       placeholders against the :class:`ExecutionContext` via\n116\t       ``templates.substitute_placeholders``.\n117\t    3. Pick a model: :attr:`model` if explicitly set, else map from\n118\t       ``ctx.prd.capability`` when :attr:`model_from_capability` is\n119\t       true, else fall back to sonnet.\n120\t    4. Pipe the composed prompt to ``claude --print`` via subprocess with\n121\t       ``--allowed-tools`` set to :attr:`tools`.\n122\t    5. Parse stdout for :attr:`sentinel_success` or :attr:`sentinel_failure`\n123\t       to decide whether the task succeeded. The agent is contracted to\n124\t       emit one of these as its final line.\n125\t\n126\t    When a subsequent :class:`ShellTask` fails with\n127\t    ``on_failure=\"retry_agent\"``, the runner re-invokes this AgentTask\n128\t    with :attr:`verify_prompts` prepended to the prompt list and\n129\t    ``{{CHECK_OUTPUT}}`` bound to the failed stdout/stderr — at most\n130\t    :attr:`retries` times.\n131\t    \"\"\"\n132\t\n133\t    name: str = \"implement\"\n134\t    prompts: list[str] = field(default_factory=list)\n135\t    tools: list[str] = field(default_factory=list)\n136\t    model: str | None = None\n137\t    model_from_capability: bool = True\n138\t    retries: int = 1\n139\t    verify_prompts: list[str] = field(default_factory=list)\n140\t    sentinel_success: str = \"PRD_EXECUTE_OK\"\n141\t    sentinel_failure: str = \"PRD_EXECUTE_FAILED\"\n142\t\n143\t\n144\t@dataclass\n145\tclass ShellTask(Task):\n146\t    \"\"\"Run a deterministic shell command inside the worktree.\n147\t\n148\t    ``cmd`` is formatted via :meth:`ExecutionContext.format_string` before\n149\t    execution (so ``{worktree}`` etc. placeholders are expanded) and runs\n150\t    with ``cwd=ctx.cwd`` (the worktree path after ``ensure_worktree``).\n151\t    ``env`` is merged into the subprocess environment.\n152\t\n153\t    :attr:`on_failure` controls the recovery path on non-zero exit. See\n154\t    the :data:`OnFailure` type alias for policy semantics.\n155\t    \"\"\"\n156\t\n157\t    name: str\n158\t    cmd: str\n159\t    on_failure: OnFailure = \"fail\"\n160\t    env: dict[str, str] = field(default_factory=dict)\n161\t\n162\t\n163\t# ---------- Workflow ----------\n164\t\n165\t\n166\tdef _default_applies_to(prd: \"PRD\", prds: dict[str, \"PRD\"]) -> bool:\n167\t    \"\"\"Default ``applies_to`` predicate — matches nothing.\n168\t\n169\t    Concrete workflows override this in their ``workflow.py`` module.\n170\t    Kept as a module-level function rather than a lambda so mypy and\n171\t    pickling (if ever needed) both behave.\n172\t    \"\"\"\n173\t    return False\n174\t\n175\t\n176\t@dataclass\n177\tclass Workflow:\n178\t    \"\"\"A named recipe for implementing one kind of PRD.\n179\t\n180\t    Authored in ``tools/prd-harness/workflows/<name>/workflow.py`` as a\n181\t    module-level ``workflow = Workflow(...)`` attribute. The loader\n182\t    discovers it, imports the module, and sets :attr:`workflow_dir` to\n183\t    the subdirectory path so AgentTask prompt paths resolve correctly.\n184\t\n185\t    :attr:`priority` orders workflows during assignment: higher numbers\n186\t    win when multiple predicates match. ``default`` has priority 0 and\n187\t    acts as a catchall. Ties are broken alphabetically by name.\n188\t    \"\"\"\n189\t\n190\t    name: str\n191\t    description: str = \"\"\n192\t    applies_to: AppliesToPredicate = field(default=_default_applies_to)\n193\t    priority: int = 0\n194\t    tasks: list[Task] = field(default_factory=list)\n195\t    workflow_dir: Path | None = None\n196\t\n197\t\n198\t# ---------- ExecutionContext ----------\n199\t\n200\t\n201\t@dataclass\n202\tclass ExecutionContext:\n203\t    \"\"\"State threaded through every task during a workflow run.\n204\t\n205\t    Tasks mutate this object in place as the workflow progresses:\n206\t\n207\t    - ``ensure_worktree`` sets :attr:`worktree_path` and :attr:`cwd`\n208\t    - The agent invoke populates :attr:`agent_output` and\n209\t      :attr:`agent_success`\n210\t    - ``create_pr`` sets :attr:`pr_url`\n211\t\n212\t    The runner creates one context at the start of ``run_workflow`` and\n213\t    passes it to each task in order. Tasks read from it (for formatting\n214\t    commit messages, composing prompts, etc.) and write to it (to record\n215\t    side effects for downstream tasks or the CLI to surface).\n216\t\n217\t    :attr:`dry_run` tells builtins, shell tasks, and the agent invoke to\n218\t    log what they WOULD do without actually invoking subprocesses, git,\n219\t    or gh. Drives the ``prd plan`` output.\n220\t    \"\"\"\n221\t\n222\t    prd: \"PRD\"\n223\t    repo_root: Path\n224\t    workflow: Workflow\n225\t    base_ref: str\n226\t    branch_name: str\n227\t    worktree_path: Path | None = None\n228\t    cwd: Path = field(default_factory=Path.cwd)\n229\t    agent_output: str | None = None\n230\t    agent_success: bool = False\n231\t    pr_url: str | None = None\n232\t    dry_run: bool = True\n233\t    logger: logging.Logger = field(\n234\t        default_factory=lambda: logging.getLogger(\"darkfactory\")\n235\t    )\n236\t    # Advisory process-level lock held by ensure_worktree for the\n237\t    # lifetime of this run. Managed by builtins + runner; tests should\n238\t    # not touch it directly.\n239\t    _worktree_lock: \"FileLock | None\" = field(default=None, repr=False)\n240\t\n241\t    def format_string(self, template: str) -> str:\n242\t        \"\"\"Expand ``{placeholder}`` tokens against context state.\n243\t\n244\t        Supported placeholders:\n245\t\n246\t        - ``{prd_id}`` — the PRD's id (e.g. ``PRD-070``)\n247\t        - ``{prd_title}`` — the PRD's title\n248\t        - ``{prd_slug}`` — the slug portion of the PRD filename\n249\t        - ``{branch}`` — the current branch name\n250\t        - ``{base_ref}`` — the base ref the branch was created from\n251\t        - ``{worktree}`` — the worktree path as a string, or ``\"\"`` if\n252\t          the worktree hasn't been created yet\n253\t\n254\t        Unknown placeholders raise ``KeyError`` (intentionally strict —\n255\t        workflow authors should catch typos early). Contrast with the\n256\t        agent prompt templater in ``templates.py``, which leaves unknown\n257\t        placeholders unchanged to allow incremental template evolution.\n258\t        \"\"\"\n259\t        return template.format(\n260\t            prd_id=self.prd.id,\n261\t            prd_title=self.prd.title,\n262\t            prd_slug=self.prd.slug,\n263\t            branch=self.branch_name,\n264\t            base_ref=self.base_ref,\n265\t            worktree=str(self.worktree_path) if self.worktree_path else \"\",\n266\t        )\n267\t\n[result-id: r4]"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_017x74usEsvHbE9fPYD9WHc8","session_id":"139194c3-2b15-46fb-ae47-01a4e87ddf0a","uuid":"c707de53-6515-4ff4-a990-61a7e6dbbfc6","timestamp":"2026-04-08T14:41:31.419Z"}
